

# Character Creation 

### ***Reflavouring:***

You’re allowed and encouraged to **re-flavour** whatever you like when it comes to creating your character. This allows you to substitute almost any details, although remember that everything must stay mechanically the same.  *Ex. for a werewolf your character could turn into a bear instead of a wolf, but they have to be some kind of were-animal)*. Your character only has the abilities conferred by their physical form and their moves, so you can only do the things that you have moves for or just the physical ability to do.

1. To get started, go into the *“Characters”* folder and open the *"DC Character Sheet TEMPLATE"*   
   \-Make a **copy** of it and rename the copy like this**:**    
   **“(your discord username)**’s character **(your characters name)”.** 

2. Playbooks are basically character classes, each one has a general theme or feeling. Take a quick look at the playbook names and choose a couple that really jump out at you to look into. Inside of each playbook are 4 sections. The first is the “main” and includes information and moves available and applicable to any characters of that playbook. The other 3 sections are the subtypes and contain the 3 different options for the characters of this book to specialize into. You may only pick one sub-type. Your character does not have to be the kind of creature described in the playbook, you may choose to be whatever you wish, though you only get the abilities that your moves give you.   
    *(You can take moves from the “Advancement Handout” for future advancements).*  
   *(Remember that your ‘**Classification**’ describes your monster type and profession/lifestyle and can be completely different from your Playbook or Subtype name. For example, a human janitor would have the classification “Human \- Janitor”. The playbook and subtype only dictate what powers your character has access to.)*  
     
3. Take some time and come up with your character. They can be any age, race, religion . Fill in their name, look, and origin/ bio. Next, choose what **3** moves from your playbook/sub-book you’ll start with. 

4. Choose “at least” one “human form” profile picture to represent what others would see when noticing you. Feel free to elaborate with more info/ images.   
- Remember, no porn, please.

5. Now fill out the rest of your sheet, choose 2 Aspects that best describe your character, choose their skills from the list below and add their stress and Consequence limits.   
- (only Physique/Will 3 and up get extra)

6. Make sure to add any important relationships they already have as connections, people that they could potentially have as NPCs in their story. You can get extra connections by checking out the city and its inhabitants, before you start and/or while you play.

- If you want some help, feel free to ask the community or the Mods.  
    
7. Finally once you're done, make sure to set the option to “anyone with this link”, and “view only”, then choose file \- move, move your sheet into the “Player Characters” folder and send a Mod the “share” link for approval.

### ***Stress and Consequences:***

These are your conflict stats and represent how well you can take abuse. By default all characters start with the ability to take 3 points of Mental Stress and 3 points of Physical Stress, as well as 1 Mental Consequence and 1 Physical Consequence. A high Will or Physique grants a bonus as well.

* ‘Physique’ \+3 or higher adds \+2 stress and a consequence, changing your totals to Physical stress cap of 5 and 2 Physical consequences.  
* ‘Will’ \+3 or higher adds \+2 stress and a consequence, changing your totals to Mental stress cap of 5 and 2 Mental consequences.

### ***Skills:***

Each skill describes a general ability that your character has an understanding of.   
\*\*Fill in the numbered squares (as described below). Higher numbers represent greater skill.\*\*  
   
Having a high score for a particular skill doesn’t mean that your character is amazing at everything to do with that subject. Rather it means they excel at some aspect of that skill. Mechanically it would be adding your shoot skill to firing a gun, but not adding it for firing a crossbow, as your character wouldn’t be proficient with crossbows. Of course which Aspects of the skill your character is proficient in, is for you to decide.

### ***Setting up/ joining scenes:***

Playing scenes is the actual game and when trying to think of what to write next ask yourself “what would my character do now?” and write them starting to try that. Always try to push onto the next interesting part of your character's story, if they aren't doing much or are waiting, use time jumps as needed. 

Take a look through the Active Characters and see if there are any who your character could cross paths with. Characters with similar upbringing, schooling, jobs, hobbies or even secrets can be a way for your character to have noticed them somewhere. 

Your character’s backstory can be a great place to get ideas for their actions in the future, why are they the way they are? What do they want to become, or do? What’s the next thing they would try to do?

### ***NPCs:*** 

There are TONS of people in the city, the busy areas and shopping districts are always full of people milling about and going about their errands, be sure to mention them and their actions in your scenes. When writing what NPCs do, always make them act the way they would most likely act. Do not make them act in a way just because you want them to. Most NPCs are just side or background characters but some are more important. Characters you think could run into other Player Characters and have interesting interactions can become “named characters” and get a character-post to save their info and story for others to interact with.
